article.description: Nicole Ohlde scored 10 of her 14 points in the second half to lead the host Minnesota Lynx to a 75-59 victory Wednesday night over the slumping Phoenix Mercury.
article.headline: Minnesota snaps 2-game skid; Phoenix drops 4 of 5
article.linkText: Ohlde provides second-half spark in Lynx win
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- The grind of a long road trip finally caught
up with the Phoenix Mercury.

Nicole Ohlde scored 10 of her 14 points in the second half to
lead the Minnesota Lynx to a 75-59 victory Wednesday night over
slumping Phoenix.

Diana Taurasi scored 14 points and Penny Taylor 12 for the
Mercury (3-9), who have played nine of their first 12 games on the
road and just finished an 0-3 trip in which they were outscored by
an average of 16 point.

On Wednesday, the second of back-to-back games for the Mercury,
they missed their first five shots and ended the night shooting a
season-low 26.4 percent in losing four the fourth time in five
games.

"We got reasonable shots most times," Mercury coach Carrie
Graf said. "It was evident that it was a back-to-back and we
didn't have a shootaround. I think that was obvious. There wasn't a
lot of legs in our shots."

Lynx coach Suzie McConnell Serio said Minnesota's defense also
was a factor in the Mercury's poor shooting.

"We were aware of them loving to shoot at the 3-point line and
being very capable of doing it," McConnell Serio said. "(We were)
just being very conscious of getting out and challenging and not
giving up uncontested threes."

The Mercury attempted a season-high 23 3-pointers but hit only
six of them.

"We had a tough night shooting the ball," Taurasi said.
"That's about it."

Vanessa Hayden and Katie Smith added 12 points apiece for the
Lynx, were coming off a pair of double-digit defeats on the West
Coast.

"Tonight was all about us getting back our confidence and
(being) where we want to be," McConnell Serio said.

Minnesota (6-5) outscored the Mercury 40-16 in the paint and
10-0 on the fastbreak, dominating both ends of the court by
dictating the tempo throughout the game. Ohlde took advantage,
scoring twice on transition baskets and three times on low-post
moves in the second half.

"I think our guards were penetrating and getting some easy
baskets, pushing the floor, allowing me to run the floor and get
easy baskets that way," Ohlde said. "It's just something I like
to use every once in a while as an advantage, depending on the
matchup I have and the tempo of the game."

Ohlde averaged just 9 points in Minnesota's last two losses but
turned it around with an efficient night against Phoenix, making
seven of nine shots, snaring six rebounds, dishing out three
assists and committing no turnovers.

"It was a tough road trip for Nicole," McConnell Serio said.
"She really struggled the last two games, and teams tend to key on
her. Tonight she was able to get baskets in transition, she was
able to put the ball on the floor and make moves, and that's when
she's at her best."

The Lynx expanded a seven-point halftime lead to 13 in the first
two minutes of the second half. Ohlde and Hayden combined to score
Minnesota's first 10 points after the break.

Taylor countered with seven quick points to keep the Mercury in
the game. But the Lynx slowly pulled away, hitting 12 straight free
throws down the stretch.
